## Running the Definition file
The `octo.yaml` is your Octo definition file.
It contains all the modules you want to run,
which will create your infrastructure resources as per the module's instructions.

Octo generates Terragrunt module folders from your definition; Terraform/Tofu (via Terragrunt) is the
executor. The flow has three steps — generate, apply, then commit the results back into Octo. An
optional validate step compares the Terraform plan against Octo's own diff.

Every Octo command locates the definition file via the `OCTO_DEFINITION_FILE_PATH` environment variable.
Pass it inline before each command, as shown below. For the apply step, export it
so Terragrunt passes it through to the `octo run-action` calls it makes mid-apply.

```bash
# 1. Generate the Terragrunt module folders into ./.octo-tf (this directory is octo-owned and wiped each run).
OCTO_DEFINITION_FILE_PATH=octo.yaml node_modules/.bin/octo generate -o .octo-tf

# 2. (optional) Produce a plan.json per module folder, then validate it against Octo's resource diff.
#    cd .octo-tf && terragrunt run-all plan -out plan.out && terragrunt run-all show -json plan.out > plan.json
OCTO_DEFINITION_FILE_PATH=octo.yaml node_modules/.bin/octo validate --terragruntDir .octo-tf

# 3. Apply with Terragrunt (export so run-action inherits it), then record the applied outputs into Octo.
export OCTO_DEFINITION_FILE_PATH=octo.yaml
cd .octo-tf && terragrunt run-all apply && cd ..
OCTO_DEFINITION_FILE_PATH=octo.yaml node_modules/.bin/octo commit --terragruntDir .octo-tf
```

> `octo run-action` is invoked automatically by Terraform mid-apply for resources whose lifecycle runs
> outside Terraform; you do not call it directly. It reads `OCTO_DEFINITION_FILE_PATH` like every other command.

## Development
The rest of the setup is a TypeScript project for you to get started with developing new modules in Octo quickly.
You can follow the official documentation to learn more.
Once you have your custom constructs and modules defined, you can use below commands to build those modules.
Don't forget to add your new modules to your Octo definition file.

```bash
npm run build
```

## Destroy
Once you have your infrastructure created, and you wish all of them destroyed,
its as simple as commenting out the necessary modules and re-running the generate → apply → commit flow.
Octo wipes and regenerates `.octo-tf`, so removed modules disappear from the Terragrunt files and
Terragrunt destroys their resources on the next apply.

### Step 1
In `octo.yaml`, comment out all modules except the `app` and `account` modules.
The app and account modules load AWS credentials to call AWS APIs, hence they remain uncommented.

By commenting the `s3-website-service-module` module below,
you are safely deleting the s3-website resources created by this module.

```yaml
modules:
  - moduleId: app-module
    moduleClass: SimpleAppModule
    moduleInputs:
      name: aws-s3-website

  - moduleId: account-module
    moduleClass: AwsIniAccountModule
    moduleInputs:
      accountId: "${env.AWS_ACCOUNT_ID}"
      app: "${{app-module.model.app}}"

  #- moduleId: s3-website-service-module
  #  moduleClass: AwsS3StaticWebsiteServiceModule
  #  moduleInputs:
  #    account: "${{account-module.model.account}}"
  #    awsRegionId: us-east-1
  #    bucketName: "${env.AWS_S3_WEBSITE_BUCKET_NAME}"
  #    directoryPath: website
```

### Step 2
Then, re-build (if necessary) and re-run the generate → apply → commit flow from "Running the Definition file".
